<h2>Autocomplete — the editable, filterable droplist</h2>
<p>The <strong>autocomplete</strong> is the richest concrete member of the <a href="/blocks/droplist/">droplist family</a>: an editable <code>&lt;input role="combobox"&gt;</code> bound to a separate <code>role="listbox"</code> surface, where typing <em>narrows</em> the collection rather than seeking within it. It is the one member that splits the substrate across two elements — the input is the focus host, the listbox is the collection — which is exactly what authoring it pressure-tests. As a form-associated custom element (<code>&lt;auto-complete&gt;</code>) it participates in <code>&lt;form&gt;</code> submission, <code>FormData</code>, reset, and validity, and it mirrors the WAI-ARIA APG <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/combobox/">Combobox</a> (<code>aria-autocomplete="list"</code>) pattern.</p>

<h3>The one idea that unlocks it — focus host ≠ collection</h3>
<p>In the <a href="/blocks/dropdown/">dropdown</a>, one element played two roles: the <code>&lt;ul role="listbox"&gt;</code> was <em>both</em> the focus host (it took <code>tabindex=0</code> and received keydown) <em>and</em> the collection holding the options. Autocomplete breaks that: DOM focus must stay on the <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> so typing is never interrupted — so the input is the <strong>focus host</strong> while the <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code> remains the <strong>collection</strong>. They are two different elements, and that single separation is the whole story of how autocomplete differs. Everything else follows from it:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Input-side = text &amp; query</strong> (<code>filter</code>, <code>clearable</code>). <strong>Listbox-side = collection &amp; active item</strong> (<code>focus-delegation</code>, <code>selection</code>, <code>anchor</code>, <code>live-status</code>, <code>windowed</code>).</p>
</blockquote>

<h3>Trait selection at a glance</h3>
<p>The autocomplete's identity is fixed by these trait selections. The two structural moves versus the dropdown are <strong>editable</strong> (the focus host becomes the input, via <code>focus-delegation</code>'s <code>controller</code>) and <strong>filter</strong> replacing <strong>type-ahead</strong> (mutually exclusive — both consume printable keys). Structural picks are <strong>local</strong> (an author cannot change them via props or ambient intent); behavioral picks are this component's <em>stance</em> and remain overridable by an ambient <code>droplistIntent</code>:</p>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Trait</th><th>Dimension</th><th>Value</th><th>Kind</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><a href="/intents/selection/">Selection</a></td><td><code>model</code></td><td><code>single</code>, <code>selectionFollowsFocus=false</code> (arrow previews, Enter commits)</td><td><strong>structural</strong></td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="/intents/focus-delegation/">Focus Delegation</a></td><td><code>strategy</code> / <code>controller</code></td><td><code>virtual</code>, <code>controller=&lt;input&gt;</code> — host is the input, not the listbox</td><td><strong>structural</strong></td></tr>
