<p>Compared to the dropdown substrate, two attributes carry the entire delta: the listbox's <code>focus-delegation</code> gains <code>;controller=city-input</code> (its host is now the input), and the input's <code>filter</code> replaces the listbox's <code>type-ahead</code>. <code>selection</code> and <code>anchored</code> are otherwise the dropdown's, with <code>selectionFollowsFocus=false</code> so arrowing previews and Enter commits.</p>

<h3>Altitude 1a — Inside <code>&lt;auto-complete&gt;</code>: the class</h3>
<p>An autocomplete does not bake in <em>which</em> options or <em>whose</em> selection — it is generic. The component class bridges the public surface (the <code>name</code>/<code>src</code> attributes, <code>value</code>, the form, events) and the private two-element substrate. Two things are non-negotiable: it is a <strong>form-associated custom element</strong> (so <code>&lt;form&gt;</code> / <code>FormData</code> / reset / validity all just work — no hidden input), and the only autocomplete-specific glue is the commit handler: <em>on commit, write the label into the input, dismiss the surface, keep focus on the input.</em></p>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-typescript">const { injectors } = window;

class AutoComplete extends HTMLElement {
  static formAssociated = true;                                  // → real form control
  static observedAttributes = ['value', 'src', 'name', 'placeholder'];

  #internals = this.attachInternals();
  #injector  = injectors.ensureInjector(this);                   // private to this element
  #input!: HTMLInputElement;                                     // the focus host
  #selected: { value: string; label: string } | null = null;
  static #counter = 0;

  connectedCallback() {
    // Public attributes → private contexts, scoped to this element's injector.
    const surfaceId = `auto-complete-${++AutoComplete.#counter}`;
    this.#injector.set('customContexts:surfaceId',   surfaceId);
    this.#injector.set('customContexts:inputId',     `${surfaceId}-input`);
    this.#injector.set('customContexts:placeholder', this.getAttribute('placeholder') ?? '');
    // `filter` reads `src` to know where to fetch matches from (async mode).
    this.#injector.set('customContexts:src',         this.getAttribute('src') ?? '');

    this.value = this.getAttribute('value') ?? '';               // initial selection
    // The inner `selection` trait commits the active option; we hear it once.
    this.addEventListener('selection-change', this.#onCommit);
  }

  // ── Form-control surface (string value, like &lt;input&gt;) ───────────────
  get value() { return this.#selected?.value ?? ''; }
  set value(v: string) {
    this.#selected = v ? { value: v, label: v } : null;          // label resolved on commit
    this.#internals.setFormValue(this.value);
  }
  get selectedOption() { return this.#selected; }

  formResetCallback() { this.value = this.getAttribute('value') ?? ''; }
  formStateRestoreCallback(state: string) { this.value = state; }

  // ── The only autocomplete-specific logic: glue on commit ──────────────
  // `filter` injects the options and `focus-delegation`+`selection` drive the
  // keyboard; the sole bespoke step is "on commit, set the input text + close".
  #onCommit = (e: CustomEvent&lt;{ value: string; label: string }&gt;) =&gt; {
    e.stopPropagation();
    this.#selected = e.detail;
    this.#input.value = e.detail.label;                          // write label into the input
    this.#internals.setFormValue(this.value);
    this.#input.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');         // anchor dismisses the surface
    this.#input.focus();                                        // focus stays on the input
    this.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('change', { detail: this.#selected, bubbles: true }));
  };
}

customElements.define('auto-complete', AutoComplete);</code></pre></we-code-view>

<p>The locals the class set — <code>@surfaceId</code>, <code>@inputId</code>, <code>@src</code>, <code>@placeholder</code> — are the <em>only</em> contexts the template references. There is no hidden input; form participation lives on the element itself via <code>ElementInternals.setFormValue</code>. The template wires the two-element substrate, naming the input as the listbox's focus controller:</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-html">&lt;input id="{{ '{{' }}@inputId}}" role="combobox"
       aria-controls="{{ '{{' }}@surfaceId}}"
       aria-autocomplete="list"
       aria-expanded="false"
       anchor="{{ '{{' }}@surfaceId}}"
       placeholder="{{ '{{' }}@placeholder}}"
       filter="async"
       clearable&gt;

&lt;ul id="{{ '{{' }}@surfaceId}}" role="listbox"
    focus-delegation="strategy=virtual;controller={{ '{{' }}@inputId}}"
    selection="model=single;selectionFollowsFocus=false"
    anchored="placement=bottom-start;collision=flip,resize"
    live-status
    popover&gt;
  &lt;!-- `filter` injects &lt;li role="option"&gt; from `src` matches; nothing authored here --&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>

<h4>Reading the pair as trait language</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Literal — structural identity.</strong> <code>filter</code> on the input, <code>focus-delegation="…;controller=…"</code> and <code>selection="model=single;selectionFollowsFocus=false"</code> on the listbox, <code>role="combobox"</code>, <code>role="listbox"</code>, <code>aria-autocomplete="list"</code>. These make this an editable, filterable autocomplete and not a dropdown or a menu; the trait language locks them. <code>filter</code> and <code>type-ahead</code> are mutually exclusive, so this member has no <code>type-ahead</code> at all.</li>
  <li><strong>Literal — behavioral, ambient-overridable.</strong> <code>anchored="placement=…;collision=…"</code>, the loader mode behind <code>filter="async"</code>, and the presence of <code>live-status</code> / <code>windowed</code>. Hardcoded as this widget's stance; the ambient <code>droplistIntent</code> injector still wins on any dimension the author has not stated.</li>
  <li><strong>Erased — focus host.</strong> No <code>tabindex</code> anywhere. The input is already focusable; <code>controller=@inputId</code> tells <code>focus-delegation</code> to attach keydown to the input and write <code>aria-activedescendant</code> onto it, while the listbox stays out of the tab order. The listbox is the collection, never the focus host.</li>
  <li><strong>Erased — open state &amp; form participation.</strong> <code>commandfor</code>/<code>anchor</code> + the platform own surface visibility and <code>aria-expanded</code>; <code>static formAssociated = true</code> + <code>setFormValue</code> own <code>FormData</code>, reset, validity, bfcache restore, <code>&lt;label for&gt;</code>, and the native <code>autocomplete</code> attribute — no hidden input.</li>
  <li><strong>Bound — options via <code>filter</code>, not authored.</strong> No <code>&lt;template for-each&gt;</code>: <code>filter</code> reads the input's text, runs the loader lifecycle against <code>@src</code> (debounce ~250ms, enter <code>filtering</code>, de-stale, inject <code>&lt;li role="option"&gt;</code>), and <code>live-status</code> announces the count on settle. The author never writes the options.</li>
  <li><strong>Bound — failure channel, symmetric to the result channel.</strong> The <code>filter</code> request carries both a <code>respond(items)</code> and a <code>reject(message?)</code> callback. When the source rejects or the request errors, the consumer calls <code>reject</code>: <code>filter</code> clears <code>aria-busy</code> and emits a <code>filter-error</code> event, which <code>live-status</code> maps to its <code>error</code> announcement out of the box (the way it maps <code>filter-request</code> → loading and <code>filter-resolved</code> → count). A stale rejection — one a newer query already aborted — is dropped, exactly like a stale <code>respond</code>; the listbox never silently hangs on <code>aria-busy</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Bound — commit glue, scoped.</strong> The <code>selection</code> trait commits the active option and fires <code>selection-change</code>; the class's <code>#onCommit</code> catches it, calls <code>stopPropagation</code>, writes the label into the input, dismisses the surface, keeps focus on the input, and re-emits a public <code>change</code> event. That handful of lines is the only genuinely autocomplete-specific logic — everything else is composed traits.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Altitude 2 — Component (the consumer call site)</h3>
<p>The element and its attributes <em>are</em> the trait selection. <code>editable</code>/<code>filter</code> are baked into this preset; the consumer points <code>src</code> at a query endpoint and reads the value.</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-html">&lt;auto-complete name="city"
               src="/api/cities?q="
               placeholder="Search a city…"
               on:change="setCity($event)"&gt;&lt;/auto-complete&gt;
&lt;!-- `filter="async"` is baked into the preset; `src` is the query endpoint the
     filter trait appends the typed text to. A `client`-mode autocomplete would
     instead receive an inline option set and filter it in place. --&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>

<h3>Altitude 3 — TypeScript, explicit composition</h3>
<p>A list of <code>with*</code> factories — structurally identical to the dropdown's, with the editable delta made explicit: <code>controller</code> on focus, <code>withFilter</code> in place of <code>withTypeAhead</code>, plus <code>clearable</code> and <code>live-status</code>:</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-typescript">const city = composeDroplist(input, [
  withAnchoredSurface({ placement: 'bottom-start', collision: ['flip', 'resize'] }),
  withFocusDelegation({ strategy: 'virtual', controller: input }),  // host is the input
  withSelection({ model: 'single', selectionFollowsFocus: false }), // arrow previews, Enter commits
  withFilter({ mode: 'async', src: '/api/cities?q=' }),             // replaces withTypeAhead
  withClearable(),                                                  // the X affordance
  withLiveStatus(),                                                 // announce counts + active option
]);
// → returns a handle; city.cleanup() reverts every trait, in reverse.</code></pre></we-code-view>
<p>Diff it against the dropdown's composition and the delta is exact: <code>controller</code> is added to focus, <code>withTypeAhead()</code> becomes <code>withFilter(...)</code>, and <code>withClearable()</code> + <code>withLiveStatus()</code> come along. <code>selection</code> and <code>anchor</code> are unchanged.</p>

<h3>Example — a project's city autocomplete</h3>
<p>A project consumes the generic <code>&lt;auto-complete&gt;</code> by pointing <code>src</code> at an endpoint and handling the commit; the component is otherwise untouched. The same element is reused for users, products, or tags by changing <code>src=</code> and the handler — never by editing the component.</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-html">&lt;form on:submit="saveTrip($event)"&gt;
  &lt;label for="city"&gt;Destination&lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;auto-complete id="city"
                 name="city"
                 src="/api/cities?q="
                 placeholder="Search a city…"
                 on:change="setCity($event)"&gt;&lt;/auto-complete&gt;

  &lt;!-- … other fields … --&gt;

  &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Save&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre></we-code-view>
<we-code-view><pre><code class="language-javascript">const { injectors } = window;

// Provide the action handlers at the document root — any &lt;auto-complete&gt; in
// the tree resolves them. The city list itself is fetched by `filter` from `src`.
const root = injectors.getInjectorOf(document);
root.set('customContexts:handlers', {
  setCity: (e) =&gt; tripStore.setItem('city', e.detail.value),
  saveTrip: (e) =&gt; {
    e.preventDefault();
    // POST tripStore state — city is the committed value string
  },
});

window.attributes.upgrade(document.body);</code></pre></we-code-view>

<h4>What the project owns vs. what the autocomplete owns</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Project</strong>: the query endpoint (<code>src</code>), the persistent selection (<code>tripStore.city</code>), the submit handler. Nothing about <em>how an autocomplete works</em>.</li>
  <li><strong><code>&lt;auto-complete&gt;</code></strong>: trait composition, the input↔listbox focus split, the filter/loader lifecycle, result announcements, single-selection commit semantics, and the public <code>change</code> event. Nothing about <em>what is in the list</em> or <em>where it comes from</em> beyond the <code>src</code> contract.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Trace — typing "par", arrow, enter</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Focus enters the input → <strong>anchor</strong> opens the surface, <code>aria-expanded="true"</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>filter</strong> hears <code>input</code> events, debounces, enters loader <code>filtering</code>, calls <code>src</code>, de-stales, injects <code>&lt;li role="option"&gt;</code> into the listbox.</li>
  <li><strong>focus-delegation</strong> re-reads the descendants (<code>aria-setsize</code>/<code>aria-posinset</code>); active stays unset — editable lists don't auto-highlight.</li>
  <li><strong>live-status</strong> announces "7 results available."</li>
  <li>User presses <strong>ArrowDown</strong> — keydown fires <em>on the input</em>; focus-delegation (listening on the controller) moves the active option and writes <code>aria-activedescendant</code> on the input. <code>selectionFollowsFocus=false</code>, so nothing commits — just a preview.</li>
  <li>User presses <strong>Enter</strong> — <strong>selection</strong> reads the active item via the input's <code>aria-activedescendant</code>, commits it, fires <code>selection-change</code>.</li>
  <li>The <code>&lt;auto-complete&gt;</code> glue (<code>#onCommit</code>) writes "Paris" into the input, <strong>anchor</strong> dismisses the surface, focus stays on the input, and <strong>clearable</strong> now shows the X (value non-empty).</li>
</ol>

<h3>Public API</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Surface</th><th>Shape</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Attribute <code>name</code></td><td>string</td><td>Form-control name; flows through to the enclosing <code>&lt;form&gt;</code>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Attribute <code>src</code></td><td>URL prefix</td><td>Query endpoint the <code>filter</code> trait appends the typed text to (async mode); omit for a <code>client</code>-mode inline option set.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Attribute <code>value</code></td><td>string</td><td>Initial committed value; mirrored to the DOM property.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Attribute <code>placeholder</code></td><td>string</td><td>Input placeholder when empty.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Attribute <code>clearable</code></td><td>boolean</td><td>Show the clear (X) affordance once the value is non-empty.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Property <code>.value</code></td><td>string</td><td>Form-submittable surface (matches <code>&lt;input&gt;.value</code>).</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Property <code>.selectedOption</code></td><td><code>{ value, label } | null</code></td><td>Rich, programmatic access to the committed option; not form-submittable.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Event <code>change</code></td><td><code>CustomEvent&lt;{ value, label }&gt;</code></td><td>Re-emitted on commit; consumers bind with <code>on:change="…"</code>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Form participation</td><td><code>static formAssociated = true</code></td><td><code>FormData</code>, reset, bfcache restore, <code>setValidity()</code>, <code>&lt;label for&gt;</code>, <code>autocomplete</code> attribute.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">The non-editable siblings are the <a href="/blocks/dropdown/">dropdown</a> (single-select) and <a href="/blocks/multi-select-dropdown/">multi-select dropdown</a>; family-level rules (intent vs. trait, three altitudes, trait surface map) live on the <a href="/blocks/droplist/">droplist family page</a>. Design history: <code>reports/2026-06-02-dropdown-trait-composition.md</code> ("Autocomplete in detail" — focus host ≠ collection, the <code>controller</code> param, type-ahead → filter, the typing trace), <code>reports/2026-06-02-droplist-trait-language.md</code> ("Autocomplete — swap one trait, move the focus host").</p>
